Although Ri recycled already known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it made gradual steps, its statements appear to be significant insofar as they do not strictly reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang's previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit ever held between an acting US President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim undertook to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump offered security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950–53 Korean war, but the United States claims that Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften the harsh international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on "denuclearization first" and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, opposing until the "declaration of the end of the war," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is exacerbating our distrust".
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the last five months, adding: "If the party interested in this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse".
