Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, who believes to be the first of its kind in the US.
The inspiration for the course arose after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, "Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?"
The young woman stated that no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, first given this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of university health services, stated that the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and about how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect to bed.
In another section participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know it won't change students' behavior instantly.
