The vast majority of the new cases result from transmissions through sexual relations, which marks a change from the past.
Traditionally, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contracted HIV in this way was reduced to almost zero, the Chinese health authorities said at a conference in Yunnan Province.
However, in terms of annual annual annual variation, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100 000 people.
The transmission of HIV through sexual intercourse is an acute problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but it is said that discrimination against the LGBT community is frequent.
Studies have estimated that, due to the country's conservative values, 70 to 90% of men who have had sexual relations with other men end up marrying women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases stem from inadequate sexual protection in these relationships.
The Chinese government has since 2003 promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to resolve the problem.
