Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, created a startup that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of this legendary character of technologies, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of the open source platform of Berners-Lee, Solid.
This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to that information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jocously stated that the underlying intention of Inrupt is to "dominate the world".
"We have to do it now," he said with regard to startup.
"It's a historic moment".
The application uses Solid's technology to allow people to create their own "personal online data storage", or POD.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It is as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available in one browser and simultaneously.
What is unique about the personal online data warehouse is that it is up to the user to decide who has access to what kind of information.
The company calls it "personal capacity through data".
The idea of Inrupt, according to CEO John Bruce, is to provide adequate resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company is currently composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some internal programmers hired to work on the project and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, world-wide technology creators will be able to create their own decentralised applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
