Rob Dewar, an advisor for nature conservation of the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland farming, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably over the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works that affect the dormitories and make the habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightnings are also a threat, together with the fly-kill papers and some chemical treatments of construction materials, in addition to the attacks of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
It is used by them a sophisticated echo localization technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76 000 hectares of land throughout the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained specialists who regularly conduct studies, room inspections, and sometimes rescues.
He also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats aios, at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
