Updated Information about the Red Tide: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in concentrations of Red Tide in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of less stain proliferation were identified in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The stain of the Red Tide extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Smudges can be found about ten miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also sighted in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations along or off the coast of Pinella County, low concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations along or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to middle concentrations in Charlotte County, bottom to high concentrations along or off the coast of Lee County, and low concentrations in Collier County were recorded.
There are still reports of respiratory irritations in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the last week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritations in the northwest of Florida.
